The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Chidambaram backs rate rejig 

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Oct. 25: Finance minister P. Chidambaram today said the increase in repo and reverse repo rates were aimed at ensuring price stability and would not have any adverse impact on industrial investments. 

 Describing it as a measured step towards moderate monetary tightening, Chidambaram said, With adequate liquidity available, there will not be any adverse impact on cost of credit for investment for productive activities. 

 The RBI kept its benchmark bank rate unchanged but hiked repo rate ? the rate at which banks borrow from the central bank ? to 6.25 per cent. RBI also raised reverse repo, the rate at which it borrows money back from banks, to 5.25 per cent. 

 The finance minister said its encouraging that the RBI has raised its forecast for GDP growth for 2005-06 from an earlier 7 per cent to 7 to 7.5 per cent. He claimed agriculture was likely to perform well and the business confidence index was at the highest level in the last 10 years. 

 There are indications of an investment boom supported by buoyant growth in credit as well as in equity finance. It is critical to maintain this investment momentum to accelerate growth further, he said in a post-credit-policy interaction with newspersons. 

 Order books, capacity utilisation, employment, exports and profit margins are expected to improve in the current quarter compared with the previous one, he said.

 Chidambaram said there were indications of an investment boom supported by buoyant growth in credit as well as in equity finance. It is critical to maintain this investment momentum to accelerate growth further, he added.

 Pointing to high global oil prices that have led to a rise in inflation not only in India but also across the world, the minister said, To contain the upside risk to price stability, strong vigil is being maintained by both the government and the RBI. 




